# Build-context excludes for the `nextjs` service specifically — its build
# context is the repo root (not next-js-boilerplate/) so the Dockerfile can
# COPY prod/nextjs.env, which lives outside next-js-boilerplate/. Everything
# else in the monorepo is irrelevant to that build, so ignore it all by
# default and allow back in only what's needed.
#
# This keeps the context transfer small — it is NOT the security boundary:
# the Dockerfile only ever COPYs next-js-boilerplate/ and prod/nextjs.env
# explicitly, so even if something here were mis-scoped, backend secrets
# (prod/app.env, prod/services/*.env) still could not end up in an image
# layer without an explicit COPY naming them.
*
!next-js-boilerplate
!next-js-boilerplate/**
!prod
!prod/nextjs.env

# Re-exclude heavy/irrelevant subpaths the blanket allow above pulled back in.
next-js-boilerplate/node_modules
next-js-boilerplate/.next
next-js-boilerplate/coverage
next-js-boilerplate/e2e
next-js-boilerplate/.git
